<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,303,151,177]" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="13">Aptinothrips</emphasis>
Haliday
</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
</heading>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="12.[151,1436,222,427]" pageId="12" pageNumber="13">
This European genus of four wingless species includes one, 
<taxonomicName box="[856,948,222,246]" class="Insecta" family="Thripidae" genus="Aptinothrips" kingdom="Animalia" order="Thysanoptera" pageId="12" pageNumber="13" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="rufus">
<emphasis box="[856,948,222,246]" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="13">A. rufus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, that is possibly the most abundant thrips worldwide. Found on grass leaves throughout the temperate world, including at high elevations in some tropical countries, 
<taxonomicName box="[268,357,294,318]" class="Insecta" family="Thripidae" genus="Aptinothrips" kingdom="Animalia" order="Thysanoptera" pageId="12" pageNumber="13" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="rufus">
<emphasis box="[268,357,294,318]" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="13">A. rufus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is common in southern 
<collectingCountry box="[628,731,294,318]" name="Australia" pageId="12" pageNumber="13">Australia</collectingCountry>
on introduced pasture grasses. It is easily recognised by the 
<number box="[1413,1428,294,318]" pageId="12" pageNumber="13" value="6.0">6</number>
- segmented antennae with an enlarged sixth segment. In 
<collectingCountry box="[809,963,330,354]" name="New Zealand" pageId="12" pageNumber="13">New Zealand</collectingCountry>
montane grasses, 
<taxonomicName box="[1181,1294,331,355]" class="Insecta" family="Thripidae" genus="Aptinothrips" kingdom="Animalia" order="Thysanoptera" pageId="12" pageNumber="13" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="stylifer">
<emphasis box="[1181,1294,331,355]" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="13">A. stylifer</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
with 
<number box="[1366,1379,330,354]" pageId="12" pageNumber="13" value="8.0">8</number>
-segmented antennae, is common, and this species may possibly be found in suitable habitats in Tasmania. 
<bibRefCitation author="Palmer" pageId="12" pageNumber="13" refString="Palmer, J. M. (1975) The grass-living genus Aptinothrips Haliday (Thysanoptera: Thripidae). Journal of Entomology (B), 44, 175 - 188." type="journal article" year="1975">
Palmer (
<number box="[159,217,402,426]" pageId="12" pageNumber="13" value="1975.0">1975</number>
)
</bibRefCitation>
provided an illustrated account of the species of 
<taxonomicName box="[775,915,403,427]" class="Insecta" family="Thripidae" genus="Aptinothrips" kingdom="Animalia" order="Thysanoptera" pageId="12" pageNumber="13" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[775,915,403,427]" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="13">Aptinothrips</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
